.TH WIPER_LT 1 "" "OWL" "Forensic Media Sterilization Utility"
.
.SH NAME
wiper \- OWL Optimized Wipe and Logging \(em Forensic Media Sterilization Utility
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B wiper
[\fIOPTIONS\fR]
\fIDEVICE\fR
.PP
.B wiper
.B \-\-list
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B wiper
is a forensic-grade media sterilization tool designed for field use.
It performs verified overwrites on block devices, detects stuck bits,
supports hardware-level erase commands for ATA and NVMe drives, captures
SMART health data, and generates tamper-resistant PDF certificates
suitable for chain-of-custody documentation.
.PP
The default operation (\fB\-\-full\fR) performs a two-pass overwrite of
\fB0xFF\fR followed by \fB0x00\fR with read-back verification after each pass.
This pattern is specifically designed to detect
.I stuck bits
\(em storage cells that are permanently fixed in either a high or low state
and cannot be reliably written to. While rare, stuck bits have been observed
on all types of storage media including hard drives, SSDs, and USB flash
storage. A stuck bit in the wrong position can cause a sector to read back
incorrectly regardless of what is written to it, which may compromise the
integrity of forensic evidence stored on that media.
.PP
.B wiper
must be run as root.
.
.SH DEVICE
The target block device path, for example
.IR /dev/sda ,
.IR /dev/sdb ,
or
.IR /dev/nvme0n1 .
The device must not have any mounted partitions. Use
.B \-\-list
to enumerate available block devices before selecting a target.
.PP
.I DEVICE
is required for all operations except
.BR \-\-list .
.
.SH OPTIONS
.
.SS Wipe Operations
.TP
.BR \-f ", " \-\-full
Full double-pass wipe and verify. Writes \fB0xFF\fR to every sector and
verifies, then writes \fB0x00\fR to every sector and verifies again. This
is the default operation if no wipe mode is specified.
.IP
This is the only operation that performs a complete stuck-bit test. See
.B STUCK BITS
below.
.TP
.BR \-z ", " \-\-zero
Single-pass null wipe and verify. Writes \fB0x00\fR to every sector and
verifies the result.
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-smart
Smart wipe. Reads every sector and only overwrites sectors that do not
already contain \fB0x00\fR. Ideal for limiting write cycles on flash media
while still ensuring all sectors are cleared. Does not verify after writing.
.TP
.BR \-c ", " \-\-check
Read-only drive map. Scans the entire device and reports what percentage
of sectors contain only null bytes. No data is written. Useful for
confirming a drive is already clear before documenting it.
.TP
.B \-\-hw\-erase
Hardware erase using the device's built-in erase command, auto-detected
by device type:
.RS
.IP \(bu 4
.B ATA/SATA:
Issues \fBhdparm \-\-security\-erase\fR. Erases all user data. The drive
typically writes \fB0x00\fR to all sectors, but this is not guaranteed by
the ATA specification. Followed by a software \fB0x00\fR verify pass.
.IP \(bu 4
.B NVMe:
Issues \fBnvme format \-\-ses=1\fR (User Data Erase). Zeros all user-accessible
data at the controller level. Followed by a software \fB0x00\fR verify pass.
.RE
.IP
Meets NIST SP 800-88r2 \fBClear\fR.
Requires
.B hdparm
(ATA) or
.B nvme\-cli
(NVMe) to be installed.
.TP
.B \-\-hw\-secure
Thorough hardware erase reaching overprovisioned sectors not accessible to the
OS, auto-detected by device type:
.RS
.IP \(bu 4
.B ATA/SATA:
Issues \fBhdparm \-\-security\-erase\-enhanced\fR. The enhanced erase command
instructs the drive controller to erase all storage cells including
overprovisioned areas, wear-leveling reserves, and remapped sectors.
.B Note:
the erase pattern is vendor-defined and may not be \fB0x00\fR. Software
verification is skipped for this reason \(em a verify pass against \fB0x00\fR
would produce false mismatches on drives that write a random or proprietary
pattern. The skipped verify is documented in the wipe certificate.
.IP \(bu 4
.B NVMe:
Issues \fBnvme sanitize \-\-sanact=2\fR (Block Erase) if supported, which
resets all NAND cells to the factory-erased state including wear-leveling
and overprovisioning reserves. Falls back to \fBnvme format \-\-ses=1\fR
if Block Erase is not supported. Followed by a software \fB0x00\fR verify pass.
.RE
.IP
Meets NIST SP 800-88r2 \fBPurge\fR.
Requires
.B hdparm
(ATA) or
.B nvme\-cli
(NVMe) to be installed.
.
.SS General Options
.TP
.B \-\-list
Enumerate all block devices visible to the system and display a table
showing device path, model, vendor, serial number, transport type, size,
and mount status. Exits after displaying the list. Does not require root.
.TP
\fB\-b\fR \fISIZE\fR, \fB\-\-blocksize\fR \fISIZE\fR
Override the default working block size in bytes. The default is
\fB1048576\fR (1\~MiB). Smaller block sizes may be appropriate for testing
or for flash media that reports 4K native sectors.
.TP
\fB\-l\fR \fIFILE\fR, \fB\-\-logfile\fR \fIFILE\fR
Write a timestamped log of all operations to \fIFILE\fR. If the file
already exists, new entries are appended. All timestamps include UTC offset.
.
.SS Certificate Options
.TP
\fB\-\-report\fR \fIPATH\fR
Generate a PDF wipe certificate and write it to \fIPATH\fR. If \fIPATH\fR
is a directory, the file is auto-named as
\fBowl_cert_\fIdevice\fB_\fItimestamp\fB.pdf\fR.
.IP
The certificate is encrypted with a random owner password to prevent
editing. It opens without a password and may be freely viewed, copied,
and printed. The owner password is never displayed or logged, making the
certificate permanently read-only.
.IP
When \fB\-\-report\fR is specified, SMART data is automatically captured
before and after the wipe (if \fBsmartctl\fR is available) and included
in the certificate.
.TP
\fB\-\-operator\fR \fINAME\fR
Record the name of the operator performing the wipe on the certificate.
Requires \fB\-\-report\fR.
.
.SH STUCK BITS
A stuck bit is a storage cell permanently fixed in either a \fBhigh\fR (\fB1\fR)
or \fBlow\fR (\fB0\fR) state that cannot be reliably overwritten. The cell will
always read back its stuck value regardless of what was written to it.
.PP
Stuck bits are uncommon but have been observed on all types of storage media:
spinning hard drives, NAND flash (SSDs, USB drives, SD cards), and optical
media. They are more likely to appear on aging or heavily used devices.
.PP
A device with a stuck bit in the wrong location may appear to have been wiped
when it has not been. A sector containing a stuck bit that was originally
set to \fB1\fR will read back as \fB1\fR even after a null wipe, because the
cell cannot change state.
.PP
The
.B \-\-full
operation detects stuck bits by exploiting their fundamental property: a cell
that is stuck cannot hold both states. By writing \fB0xFF\fR (all bits high),
verifying, then writing \fB0x00\fR (all bits low) and verifying again, any
sector that fails either verify pass has cells that could not change state.
.PP
Hardware erase commands (\fB\-\-hw\-erase\fR, \fB\-\-hw\-secure\fR) do
.I not
perform a stuck-bit test. They delegate erasure to the drive controller, which
does not report individual cell states. These operations serve a different
forensic purpose: erasing overprovisioned areas that are inaccessible to the OS.
For full stuck-bit detection, use \fB\-\-full\fR.
.
.SH HARDWARE ERASE VS SOFTWARE WIPE
Storage devices contain more physical storage than they advertise to the
operating system. The hidden capacity is used for:
.IP \(bu 4
.B Wear leveling
\(em distributing writes evenly across NAND cells to extend drive lifetime
.IP \(bu 4
.B Overprovisioning
\(em reserved capacity held by the controller for performance and endurance
.IP \(bu 4
.B Remapped sectors
\(em sectors the controller has marked bad and replaced with spare cells
.PP
A software wipe (including \fB\-\-full\fR) can only write to sectors the OS
can address. Data in remapped, overprovisioned, or wear-leveled areas that
the controller has moved out of the addressable space cannot be reached by
software overwriting.
.PP
Hardware erase commands (\fB\-\-hw\-erase\fR, \fB\-\-hw\-secure\fR) instruct
the drive controller directly, allowing it to erase all physical storage
including these hidden areas. For this reason, NIST SP 800-88r2 classifies
hardware sanitize commands as
.B Purge
(higher assurance) while software overwrite is classified as
.BR Clear .
.
.SH WIPE STANDARDS
The wipe standard is automatically assigned on the certificate based on the
operation performed. No user input is required.
.TP
.B NIST SP 800-88r2 \(em Clear
(Chandramouli & Hibbard, September 2025)
One or more passes of a fixed overwrite pattern applied to all addressable
storage. Data recovery from the media using standard laboratory techniques is
not possible. Assigned to \fB\-\-full\fR, \fB\-\-zero\fR, and \fB\-\-hw\-erase\fR.
.TP
.B NIST SP 800-88r2 \(em Purge
(Chandramouli & Hibbard, September 2025)
Media-specific technique that targets all storage including data not
addressable using standard read and write commands. Renders data recovery
infeasible even with state-of-the-art laboratory techniques. Assigned to
\fB\-\-hw\-secure\fR (ATA Enhanced Security Erase or NVMe Block Erase Sanitize).
.PP
Full standard: https://doi.org/10.6028/NIST.SP.800-88r2
.PP
.TS
l l.
\fBOperation\fR	\fBAssigned Standard\fR
\fB\-\-full\fR	NIST SP 800-88r2 Clear (two-pass 0xFF/0x00 with stuck-bit detection)
\fB\-\-zero\fR	NIST SP 800-88r2 Clear
\fB\-\-hw\-erase\fR	NIST SP 800-88r2 Clear
\fB\-\-hw\-secure\fR	NIST SP 800-88r2 Purge
\fB\-\-smart\fR	Non-standard (partial overwrite, selective sectors only)
\fB\-\-check\fR	N/A (read-only operation)
.TE
.
.SH SYSTEM DEPENDENCIES
The following system tools must be installed separately via your package manager.
Python packages are listed in \fBrequirements.txt\fR.
.TP
.B hdparm
Required for \fB\-\-hw\-erase\fR and \fB\-\-hw\-secure\fR on ATA/SATA devices.
.RS
Debian/Ubuntu: \fBapt install hdparm\fR
.RE
.TP
.B nvme\-cli
Required for \fB\-\-hw\-erase\fR and \fB\-\-hw\-secure\fR on NVMe devices.
.RS
Debian/Ubuntu: \fBapt install nvme\-cli\fR
.RE
.TP
.B smartmontools
Required for SMART data capture when using \fB\-\-report\fR. If not installed,
SMART sections are omitted from the certificate without error.
.RS
Debian/Ubuntu: \fBapt install smartmontools\fR
.RE
.
.SH EXAMPLES
List available block devices (does not require root):
.RS
.B wiper \-\-list
.RE
.PP
Full double-pass wipe with stuck-bit detection (default operation):
.RS
.B sudo wiper /dev/sdb
.RE
.PP
Full wipe with log file and PDF certificate:
.RS
.B sudo wiper /dev/sdb \-l /var/log/wipe.log \-\-report /cases/certs/
.RE
.PP
Full wipe with certificate, operator name, and explicit wipe standard:
.RS
.B sudo wiper /dev/sdb \-\-report ./certs/ \-\-operator "Jane Smith"
.RE
.PP
Hardware erase (auto-detects ATA or NVMe) with certificate:
.RS
.B sudo wiper /dev/sdb \-\-hw\-erase \-\-report ./certs/
.RE
.PP
Hardware secure erase on NVMe (Block Erase + software verify):
.RS
.B sudo wiper /dev/nvme0n1 \-\-hw\-secure \-\-report ./certs/
.RE
.PP
Check whether a drive is already clear (read-only, no writes):
.RS
.B sudo wiper /dev/sdb \-\-check
.RE
.PP
Smart wipe on a USB flash drive (only rewrites non-null sectors):
.RS
.B sudo wiper /dev/sdc \-\-smart
.RE
.
.SH CONFIRMATION
All destructive operations require the operator to confirm by typing the exact
device path at the prompt before the wipe begins. This prevents accidental
erasure of the wrong device.
.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /proc/sys/vm/drop_caches
Written to before each read pass to flush the kernel page cache and ensure
reads come from disk rather than memory. Requires root.
.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Error (device not found, permission denied, I/O failure, unsupported hardware).
.TP
.B 130
Interrupted by the user (Ctrl+C).
.
.SH NOTES
\fBwiper\fR opens block devices with \fBO_SYNC\fR to bypass the kernel write
cache and ensure all writes reach the physical device before proceeding.
.PP
The \fB\-\-smart\fR option is particularly well-suited to NAND flash media
because it limits write cycles by only overwriting sectors that are not already
null, reducing wear on cells with a finite write endurance.
.PP
Wipe certificates are encrypted PDF files. They open without a password and
support viewing, copying, and printing, but editing is locked with a
cryptographically random owner password that is never stored or displayed.
This makes the certificate tamper-evident: any modification requires
regenerating it, which would produce a different document.
.
